[{"categories":["Security"],"date":"2025-04-17T00:00:00Z","id":"/notes/euvd/","keywords":[],"summary":"\u003cp\u003eThe European Union Agency for Cybersecurity (ENISA) has its own Vulnerability Database, called the \u003ca href=\"https://euvd.enisa.europa.eu\"\u003eEuropean Union Vulnerability Database (EUVD)\u003c/a\u003e. It\u0026rsquo;s datasource is \u003ca href=\"https://www.vulnerability-lookup.org\"\u003eThe Vulnerability Lookup project\u003c/a\u003e, a system that correlates various sources and streamlines Coordinated Vulnerability Disclosure (CVD). It uses the Global CVE Allocation System (\u003ca href=\"https://gcve.eu\"\u003elink\u003c/a\u003e) as a source. This system is created with funding by the EU and is maintained by Computer Incident Response Center Luxembourg (CIRCL), with a nice dashboard \u003ca href=\"https://vulnerability.circl.lu\"\u003ehere\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","tags":[],"title":"European Union Vulnerability Database"},{"categories":["Programming"],"date":"2025-04-15T00:00:00Z","id":"/notes/developer-growth/","keywords":[],"summary":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"http://cleancoder.com/\"\u003eUncle Bob\u003c/a\u003e, in his presentations, likes to say that the number of developers in the world doubles every 5 years. Recently The Primeagen in one of his \u003ca href=\"https://youtube.com/shorts/42S4YPUK8N4?si=lB-6tHBJfpi4dfYi\"\u003eshorts\u003c/a\u003e he echos that statement. They both do not give any source for this information, so can it be validated?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe Netherlands has an agency called \u003ca href=\"https://www.cbs.nl\"\u003eCentraal Bureau voor de Statistiek (CBS)\u003c/a\u003e which collects all kinds of statistics about the country. It turns out that they also have statistics on the type of field people work in.\u003c/p\u003e","tags":[],"title":"Developer Growth"},{"categories":["Programming","Emacs"],"date":"2025-01-09T20:25:59+01:00","id":"/notes/clojure-emacs/","keywords":[],"summary":"\u003cp\u003eEmacs ðŸ¥° Lisp, and as \u003ca href=\"/notes/clojure/\" class=\"backlink\"\u003eClojure\u003c/a\u003e\n is a Lisp like language, Emacs is extremely capable in editing it. I use several packages to make my live a joy inside Emacs, here are the \u003ca href=\"/notes/clojure/\" class=\"backlink\"\u003eClojure\u003c/a\u003e\n specific packages:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://paredit.org/\"\u003eparedit\u003c/a\u003e: I highly recommend it to work with any lisp, it makes working with the parenthesis a real joy. There is an \u003ca href=\"http://danmidwood.com/content/2014/11/21/animated-paredit.html\"\u003eanimated guide\u003c/a\u003e of most of the features.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://cider.mx/\"\u003ecider\u003c/a\u003e: The only thing you need to run and work with Clojure files\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://github.com/borkdude/flycheck-clj-kondo\"\u003eflycheck-clj-kondo\u003c/a\u003e: brings the hints from \u003ca href=\"https://github.com/clj-kondo/clj-kondo\"\u003eclj-kondo\u003c/a\u003e to the editing screen.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://github.com/clojure-emacs/clj-refactor.el\"\u003eclj-refactor\u003c/a\u003e: provides all the refactoring tools you will need\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://github.com/clojure-emacs/clojure-mode\"\u003eclojure-mode\u003c/a\u003e: finally the clojure mode to provide basic features (highlighting, indentation, navigation and basic refactoring) into Emacs.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI have an \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLdKXxqwRv6_y7rHHjbrK38E59t9ost3o3\"\u003eYouTube playlist\u003c/a\u003e on my channel that covers most of these tools. The videos are from 2016 (when I did my live coding in Clojure series), but are still very relevant today.\u003c/p\u003e","tags":[],"title":"Setting up Emacs for Clojure development"},{"categories":["Programming"],"date":"2025-01-07T22:18:54+01:00","id":"/notes/clojure/","keywords":[],"summary":"\u003cp\u003eThe Clojure programming language. It is a functional programming language on top of dthe JVM. It is a Lisp like language.\u003c/p\u003e","tags":[],"title":"The Clojure programming language"},{"categories":["Programming","Emacs"],"date":"2025-01-07T00:00:00Z","id":"/notes/rust-emacs/","keywords":[],"summary":"\u003cp\u003eEmacs is great for editing \u003ca href=\"/notes/rust/\" class=\"backlink\"\u003eRust\u003c/a\u003e\n source files. In addition to your normal Emacs configuration (such as completion modes) it requires 3 packages. First you will want \u003ccode\u003elsp-mode\u003c/code\u003e, a very full featured LSP client for Emacs. Additionally you will want \u003ccode\u003elsp-ui\u003c/code\u003e, which I only use for the \u003ccode\u003elsp-ui-imenu\u003c/code\u003e feature.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eFinally you will want to use \u003ccode\u003erustic\u003c/code\u003e as primary editing mode for \u003ca href=\"/notes/rust/\" class=\"backlink\"\u003eRust\u003c/a\u003e\n files.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cfigure class=\"codeblock not-prose relative scroll-mt-8\" id=\"codeblock-01\"\u003e\n  \u003caside\n    class=\"absolute right-0 top-0 hidden rounded-bl-sm rounded-tr-sm bg-white/10 px-2 py-1 text-white/70 transition-opacity md:inline-block\"\n  \u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"codeblock-meta flex max-w-xs flex-row items-center space-x-3\"\u003e\n      \u003cdiv class=\"small-caps shrink cursor-default truncate font-mono text-xs\" aria-hidden=\"true\"\u003e\n        \u003cspan class=\"relative\"\u003eelisp\u003c/span\u003e\n      \u003c/div\u003e\n      \u003cdiv\u003e\n        \u003cclipboard-copy\n          type=\"button\"\n          aria-label=\"Copy code to clipboard\"\n          title=\"Copy code to clipboard\"\n          class=\"block cursor-pointer transition-colors hover:text-sky-400\"\n          target=\"#codeblock-01 code\"\n        \u003e\n          \u003csvg\n  xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"\n  fill=\"none\"\n  stroke=\"currentColor\"\n  stroke-width=\"2\"\n  stroke-linecap=\"round\"\n  stroke-linejoin=\"round\"\n  class=\"lucide lucide-clipboard h-4 w-4\"\n  viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\"\n\u003e\n  \u003crect width=\"8\" height=\"4\" x=\"8\" y=\"2\" rx=\"1\" ry=\"1\" /\u003e\n  \u003cpath d=\"M16 4h2a2 2 0 0 1 2 2v14a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H6a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V6a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h2\" /\u003e\n\u003c/svg\u003e\n\n        \u003c/clipboard-copy\u003e\n      \u003c/div\u003e\n      \u003cdiv\u003e\n        \u003ca\n          href=\"#codeblock-01\"\n          class=\"block\"\n          aria-label=\"Link to this code block\"\n          title=\"Link to this code block\"\n        \u003e\n          \u003csvg\n  xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"\n  width=\"16\"\n  height=\"16\"\n  fill=\"none\"\n  stroke=\"currentColor\"\n  stroke-linecap=\"round\"\n  stroke-linejoin=\"round\"\n  stroke-width=\"2\"\n  class=\"lucide lucide-link w-4 h-4 block\"\n  viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\"\n\u003e\n  \u003cpath d=\"M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71\" /\u003e\n  \u003cpath d=\"M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71\" /\u003e\n\u003c/svg\u003e\n\n        \u003c/a\u003e\n      \u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n  \u003c/aside\u003e\n  \u003cp class=\"sr-only\"\u003eelisp code snippet start\u003c/p\u003e","tags":[],"title":"Configuring Emacs for Rust development"},{"categories":["Programming"],"date":"2025-01-05T00:00:00Z","id":"/notes/rust/","keywords":[],"summary":"\u003cp\u003eThis is the rust programming language\u003c/p\u003e","tags":[],"title":"The Rust programming language"},{"categories":["Design"],"date":"2025-01-05T00:00:00Z","id":"/notes/type-driven-design/","keywords":[],"summary":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"/notes/rust/\" class=\"backlink\"\u003eRust\u003c/a\u003e\n has allows for a pattern called Type-Driven Design. In the below example a \u003ccode\u003eSubscriberName\u003c/code\u003e is created. It has a single \u003ccode\u003eString\u003c/code\u003e value. In \u003cem\u003esimple\u003c/em\u003e code this might be represented as \u003ccode\u003elet subscriber_name = \u0026quot;Arjen\u0026quot;.to_string();\u003c/code\u003e. By making the type you can wrap the validation logic into the creation of the type. This means that wherever you get a paramter of type \u003ccode\u003eSubscriberName\u003c/code\u003e you know it is valid.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cfigure class=\"codeblock not-prose relative scroll-mt-8\" id=\"codeblock-01\"\u003e\n  \u003caside\n    class=\"absolute right-0 top-0 hidden rounded-bl-sm rounded-tr-sm bg-white/10 px-2 py-1 text-white/70 transition-opacity md:inline-block\"\n  \u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"codeblock-meta flex max-w-xs flex-row items-center space-x-3\"\u003e\n      \u003cdiv class=\"small-caps shrink cursor-default truncate font-mono text-xs\" aria-hidden=\"true\"\u003e\n        \u003cspan class=\"relative\"\u003erust\u003c/span\u003e\n      \u003c/div\u003e\n      \u003cdiv\u003e\n        \u003cclipboard-copy\n          type=\"button\"\n          aria-label=\"Copy code to clipboard\"\n          title=\"Copy code to clipboard\"\n          class=\"block cursor-pointer transition-colors hover:text-sky-400\"\n          target=\"#codeblock-01 code\"\n        \u003e\n          \u003csvg\n  xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"\n  fill=\"none\"\n  stroke=\"currentColor\"\n  stroke-width=\"2\"\n  stroke-linecap=\"round\"\n  stroke-linejoin=\"round\"\n  class=\"lucide lucide-clipboard h-4 w-4\"\n  viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\"\n\u003e\n  \u003crect width=\"8\" height=\"4\" x=\"8\" y=\"2\" rx=\"1\" ry=\"1\" /\u003e\n  \u003cpath d=\"M16 4h2a2 2 0 0 1 2 2v14a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H6a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V6a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h2\" /\u003e\n\u003c/svg\u003e\n\n        \u003c/clipboard-copy\u003e\n      \u003c/div\u003e\n      \u003cdiv\u003e\n        \u003ca\n          href=\"#codeblock-01\"\n          class=\"block\"\n          aria-label=\"Link to this code block\"\n          title=\"Link to this code block\"\n        \u003e\n          \u003csvg\n  xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"\n  width=\"16\"\n  height=\"16\"\n  fill=\"none\"\n  stroke=\"currentColor\"\n  stroke-linecap=\"round\"\n  stroke-linejoin=\"round\"\n  stroke-width=\"2\"\n  class=\"lucide lucide-link w-4 h-4 block\"\n  viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\"\n\u003e\n  \u003cpath d=\"M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71\" /\u003e\n  \u003cpath d=\"M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71\" /\u003e\n\u003c/svg\u003e\n\n        \u003c/a\u003e\n      \u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n  \u003c/aside\u003e\n  \u003cp class=\"sr-only\"\u003erust code snippet start\u003c/p\u003e","tags":[],"title":"Type-Driven Design"},{"categories":["Literature"],"date":"2025-01-05T00:00:00Z","id":"/notes/zero2prod/","keywords":[],"summary":"\u003cp\u003eA book about making production systems in the \u003ca href=\"/notes/rust/\" class=\"backlink\"\u003eRust\u003c/a\u003e\n programming language.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWebsite: \u003ca href=\"https://www.zero2prod.com/index.html\"\u003ehttps://www.zero2prod.com/index.html\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","tags":[],"title":"Zero to Production"}]
